Example of Text-to-Image and Image-to-Text Generation

Lecture Date: 2025-04-21

Featuring: Stable Diffusion XL (TtoI) and ViT-GPT2 (ItoT)

DO NOT run this notebook on the CS JupyterHub - there are no GPUs there (so it will take too long) AND you will fill up your home directory with packages and model files that need to be downloaded. Make sure you use TAMU or other resources.

A small example of generating images from text and back again...

Important: You must be have an Nvidia GPU and working CUDA installation to run this code!

Install the preprequisites

Note that you will need to restart your kernel after running the installation command below to ensure that the packages will load properly.

Set up the Text to Image Pipeline

This will download the model from the web... to be sure there will be a lot of packages and model data in your home directory after this. Be sure to check your ~/local and ~/.cache directories if you need to clean them out - for the most part, the info in these directories is optional. You can typically delete them and then restart your JupyterLab (or other) session. This will clean up the installation, but the packages will need to be reinstalled later and model weights repulled.

In [1]:
from diffusers import DiffusionPipeline
import torch

pipe = DiffusionPipeline.from_pretrained("stabilityai/stable-diffusion-xl-base-1.0", torch_dtype=torch.float16, use_safetensors=True, variant="fp16")
pipe.to("cuda")

# if using torch < 2.0
# pipe.enable_xformers_memory_efficient_attention()

Use the Image to Text Pipeline

You might need to restart the kernel and jump back to here after saving the image... the RTX 2080 I am using above only has 12Gb of GPU RAM and you can't fit both models on the card at the same time.

In [1]:
from transformers import pipeline

image_to_text = pipeline("image-to-text", model="nlpconnect/vit-gpt2-image-captioning")

Using a slow image processor as `use_fast` is unset and a slow processor was saved with this model. `use_fast=True` will be the default behavior in v4.48, even if the model was saved with a slow processor. This will result in minor differences in outputs. You'll still be able to use a slow processor with `use_fast=False`.
Device set to use cuda:0
In [2]:
image_to_text("image.png")

The attention mask is not set and cannot be inferred from input because pad token is same as eos token. As a consequence, you may observe unexpected behavior. Please pass your input's `attention_mask` to obtain reliable results.
We strongly recommend passing in an `attention_mask` since your input_ids may be padded. See https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/troubleshooting#incorrect-output-when-padding-tokens-arent-masked.
You may ignore this warning if your `pad_token_id` (50256) is identical to the `bos_token_id` (50256), `eos_token_id` (50256), or the `sep_token_id` (None), and your input is not padded.
